{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566331"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:39:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:39:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18789"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18789"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.17,0.15,0.44,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11522"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78669"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11522"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18789"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64012"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2907"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26928"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35355"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43706"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78669"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with three days of vomiting and diarrhoea. He has a medical history of atrial fibrillation, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and hypertension. His regular medications include amiodarone, dapagliflozin, ramipril, chlorthalidone and metformin. He appears dehydrated. His pulse rate is 98/min, blood pressure 100/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Blood tests reveal creatinine 180 \u03bcmol/L (65-110) and urea 15 mmol/L (3.0-8.0).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications would be appropriate to continue on admission?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dapagliflozin","Ramipril","Metformin","Amiodarone","Chlorthalidone"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute kidney injury (AKI) likely due to hypovolaemia from gastroenteritis. When managing medications during AKI, it is important to identify and temporarily cease those that could worsen kidney function or accumulate to toxic levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily metabolised by the liver and does not significantly affect renal function. It can be safely continued during an episode of AKI, particularly as maintaining rate control in atrial fibrillation remains important. Ensuring electrolytes are optimised is important in this patient, as the disturbance caused by vomiting and diarrhoea may result in arrhythmias. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDapagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E, a sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 (SGLT2) inhibitor, should be stopped during acute illness due to its blood-pressure lowering and diuretic properties. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERamipril\u003C/strong\u003E, an ACE inhibitor, should be temporarily ceased as it affects renal autoregulation and can worsen AKI, particularly in hypovolaemic states. It can be restarted once the patient is euvolaemic and renal function has improved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetformin\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily excreted by the kidneys and can accumulate during AKI. It should be temporarily ceased until renal function improves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChlorthalidone\u003C/strong\u003E is a thiazide-like diuretic medication, which should be stopped during acute illness due to its blood-pressure lowering and diuretic properties. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle in managing medications during AKI is to temporarily cease those that could worsen renal function or accumulate to toxic levels, while continuing medications that are essential and safe. Regular medication review and reintroduction should occur as renal function improves.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The key principle in managing medications during AKI is to temporarily cease those that could worsen renal function or accumulate to toxic levels, while continuing medications that are essential and safe."],"references":["Florek JB, Girzadas D, Lucas A. Amiodarone. National Library of Medicine. In: StatPearls [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482154/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64012"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18789"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64012"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T22:36:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T22:36:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11522"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78669"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/